            <crm:P78_is_identified_by>7th/13th centuryHe studied at the Madrasa al-Rawāḥiyya in Damascus. There he first studied medicine but then he went over to Islamic learning. He began to write in 655/1257 and  in 665/1267 he was called to the al-Ašrafiyya dār al-ḥadīt in Damascus in succession to Abū Šāma. His reputation as a scholar -and as a jurist above all- was enormous
